HE was convicted for rape, murder and robbery and spent more than 12 years in jail. Kwalang Tlou is now fighting to turn his life around and cleans dirty kasi toilets to give back to his community. He started last year after he saw a pregnant woman use the dirty toilets at Bekkersdal Taxi Rank. “The toilets now welcome commuters with an appealing smell,” he said. READ: Skip the flush and save the environment Commuters thank him by giving him the little money they have. He teamed up with two friends and they dream of having a cleaning company. Kwalang’s partner, Maweto Mlumba, also an ex-convict, said the project helped shape their thinking. Local taxi association bosses helped them with sanitisers and put a burglar door to prevent nyaope addicts from damaging infrastructure. A taxi driver thanked Kwalang for volunteering to look after the toilets. Commuter Madeline Lwazi said: “We thank them for taking care of us.” The men appealed to businesspeople to help with safety apparel and to plumbers to help fix leaking pipes.